{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-js","path":"/local-environment/","webpackCompilationHash":"","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>My early experiences with web design and development only involved the front end - HTML, CSS and some JavaScript. As long as I had a browser, I was set. Eventually as a web developer, you get to a point where you need to implement PHP or some other back-end language. Maybe you need to install Wordpress or some other CMS, but you have no idea how to do that or what it entails. Whatever the case, it's impossible to be a serious developer without knowing how to work with a server.</p>\n<p>The best way to get used to working on a server is to set up a local environment on your computer. If you know HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, but have never used PHP offline, this tutorial is for you.</p>\n<h4 id=\"goals\"><a href=\"#goals\" aria-label=\"goals permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Goals</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Set up a local \"LAMP Stack\" style environment - <code class=\"language-text\">http://localhost:8888</code></li>\n<li>Be able to run multiple servers, or \"virtual hosts\" - <code class=\"language-text\">http://custom-host.dev</code></li>\n</ul>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If you would like to learn how to set up a local environment with Vagrant and VirtualBox instead, <a href=\"/what-are-vagrant-and-virtualbox-and-how-do-i-use-them/\">visit this article</a>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h2 id=\"a-little-about-php\"><a href=\"#a-little-about-php\" aria-label=\"a little about php permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>A Little About PHP</h2>\n<p>Any HTML file can be a PHP file. Take any <code class=\"language-text\">.html</code> file you have right now and save it as a <code class=\"language-text\">.php</code> file and try to open it. What happens?</p>\n<p>I just did this with a basic HTML skeleton. If I had saved the file as <code class=\"language-text\">index.html</code>, all I would see is \"Hello, world!\". However, I saved it as <code class=\"language-text\">index.php</code> and this is what I got.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 561px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/c8192680bb6f84b627d28efc7ac618f3/d2b4f/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.27.59-PM.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 56.86274509803921%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screen Shot 2015 10 16 at 9 27 59 PM\"\n        title=\"Screen Shot 2015 10 16 at 9 27 59 PM\"\n        src=\"/static/c8192680bb6f84b627d28efc7ac618f3/d2b4f/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.27.59-PM.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/c8192680bb6f84b627d28efc7ac618f3/0cb30/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.27.59-PM.png 213w,\n/static/c8192680bb6f84b627d28efc7ac618f3/a67b6/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.27.59-PM.png 425w,\n/static/c8192680bb6f84b627d28efc7ac618f3/d2b4f/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.27.59-PM.png 561w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 561px) 100vw, 561px\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Okay...it looks like the browser is treating my PHP file as a text file. All it's doing is spitting the code right back at me. Well, that's completely useless. How do I get it to start interpreting the code?</p>\n<p>That's where the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LAMP_(software_bundle)\">LAMP stack</a> comes in. <strong>LAMP</strong> stands for <strong>L</strong>inux, <strong>A</strong>pache, <strong>M</strong>ySQL, <strong>P</strong>HP(/Python/Perl). It's an open source bundle of software applications that creates a dynamic web server environment. There is also MAMP and WAMP, for Mac and Windows, respectively.</p>\n<p>To get PHP to start working, we don't need to understand how it works, anymore than you need to understand how an internal combustion engine works to drive a car. All I want at this point is my <code class=\"language-text\">index.php</code> to start interpreting code and markup.</p>\n<p>There are two parts to this process: part one is getting your local environment set up in the first place; part two is setting up virtual hosts so you can access multiple local environments at once.</p>\n<h2 id=\"part-1-setting-up-a-local-environment\"><a href=\"#part-1-setting-up-a-local-environment\" aria-label=\"part 1 setting up a local environment permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Part 1: Setting up a Local Environment</h2>\n<p>There are complicated ways to go about installing each component of the LAMP stack one by one - or you can download a program that does it for you. You can think of it as the difference between building your own computer from parts or buying one that's already put together. They both get you to the same end point, but perhaps you want extreme amounts of control or customizability. Well, we don't.</p>\n<p>Whether you have a PC or a Mac, just <a href=\"https://www.mamp.info/en/downloads/\">download MAMP</a> and install it on your computer.</p>\n<p>Once the installation is complete and you open it, you end up at a screen like this.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 532px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/b6b1a3ca8f4fc0b8851e5daf04f949cb/72ec8/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.43.43-PM.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 75%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screen Shot 2015 10 16 at 9 43 43 PM\"\n        title=\"Screen Shot 2015 10 16 at 9 43 43 PM\"\n        src=\"/static/b6b1a3ca8f4fc0b8851e5daf04f949cb/72ec8/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.43.43-PM.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/b6b1a3ca8f4fc0b8851e5daf04f949cb/0cb30/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.43.43-PM.png 213w,\n/static/b6b1a3ca8f4fc0b8851e5daf04f949cb/a67b6/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.43.43-PM.png 425w,\n/static/b6b1a3ca8f4fc0b8851e5daf04f949cb/72ec8/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.43.43-PM.png 532w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 532px) 100vw, 532px\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Now click on <code class=\"language-text\">Start Servers</code>. If you're not in the administrator account, you might be prompted for the admin password. Once it's glowing green, everything is good to go. MAMP should open the WebStart page in a new tab in your browser. If not, you can click on <code class=\"language-text\">Open WebStart page</code> and it should take you to a page like this.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 692px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/e6ba70f5258606e164b5bb657544ab82/cbf4c/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.52.42-PM.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 73.98843930635837%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screen Shot 2015 10 16 at 9 52 42 PM\"\n        title=\"Screen Shot 2015 10 16 at 9 52 42 PM\"\n        src=\"/static/e6ba70f5258606e164b5bb657544ab82/cbf4c/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.52.42-PM.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/e6ba70f5258606e164b5bb657544ab82/0cb30/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.52.42-PM.png 213w,\n/static/e6ba70f5258606e164b5bb657544ab82/a67b6/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.52.42-PM.png 425w,\n/static/e6ba70f5258606e164b5bb657544ab82/cbf4c/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.52.42-PM.png 692w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 692px) 100vw, 692px\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>If you got a page like this, congratulations. You now have a local server and can run all the PHP you want. Go to <code class=\"language-text\">Preferences &gt; Web Server</code>. Click on the folder next to document root and choose the directory you decided to place your PHP file in from earlier. Mine was <code class=\"language-text\">sites/learnphp</code>.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 531px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/aacbdbf8e21eead8a47bf6a642f348a9/90647/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.49.42-PM.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 76.45951035781545%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screen Shot 2015 10 16 at 9 49 42 PM\"\n        title=\"Screen Shot 2015 10 16 at 9 49 42 PM\"\n        src=\"/static/aacbdbf8e21eead8a47bf6a642f348a9/90647/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.49.42-PM.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/aacbdbf8e21eead8a47bf6a642f348a9/0cb30/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.49.42-PM.png 213w,\n/static/aacbdbf8e21eead8a47bf6a642f348a9/a67b6/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.49.42-PM.png 425w,\n/static/aacbdbf8e21eead8a47bf6a642f348a9/90647/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.49.42-PM.png 531w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 531px) 100vw, 531px\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Now I'm going to go to <code class=\"language-text\">http://localhost:8888</code> in my browser. What happens?</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 265px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/bb8e32304770fefb8081579d12358cc8/3e8ea/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.58.15-PM.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 55.094339622641506%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screen Shot 2015 10 16 at 9 58 15 PM\"\n        title=\"Screen Shot 2015 10 16 at 9 58 15 PM\"\n        src=\"/static/bb8e32304770fefb8081579d12358cc8/3e8ea/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.58.15-PM.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/bb8e32304770fefb8081579d12358cc8/0cb30/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.58.15-PM.png 213w,\n/static/bb8e32304770fefb8081579d12358cc8/3e8ea/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-9.58.15-PM.png 265w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 265px) 100vw, 265px\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>It's rendering the code! PHP is being parsed by all that stuff in the LAMP stack, and outputting regular HTML. But, we only had HTML to begin with. I want some sort of proof that this was all worth it. What's something simple that HTML can't do that PHP can?</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Note for Windows users: the URL will simply be <code class=\"language-text\">localhost</code>, without the :8888.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The absolute beauty of PHP is that it can be inserted anywhere into HTML. Anything that goes inside the opening tag of <code class=\"language-text\">&lt;?php</code> and the closing tag of <code class=\"language-text\">?&gt;</code> work it's magic on your server and return HTML.</p>\n<p>I'm going to change my \"Hello, world!\".</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"php\"><pre class=\"language-php\"><code class=\"language-php\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;</span>p</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span>Hello, world! The year is <span class=\"token php language-php\"><span class=\"token delimiter important\">&lt;?php</span> <span class=\"token keyword\">echo</span> <span class=\"token function\">date</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token single-quoted-string string\">'Y'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span> <span class=\"token delimiter important\">?></span></span>.<span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;/</span>p</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span></code></pre></div>\n<p>The code <code class=\"language-text\">&lt;?php echo date(&#39;Y&#39;); ?&gt;</code> uses a date function to find the year. The HTML interpreted is just \"2015\".</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 268px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/90cd01706004760eff1692c3e8981f0a/8adc6/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-10.07.06-PM.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 49.25373134328358%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screen Shot 2015 10 16 at 10 07 06 PM\"\n        title=\"Screen Shot 2015 10 16 at 10 07 06 PM\"\n        src=\"/static/90cd01706004760eff1692c3e8981f0a/8adc6/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-10.07.06-PM.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/90cd01706004760eff1692c3e8981f0a/0cb30/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-10.07.06-PM.png 213w,\n/static/90cd01706004760eff1692c3e8981f0a/8adc6/Screen-Shot-2015-10-16-at-10.07.06-PM.png 268w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 268px) 100vw, 268px\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>That concludes the scope of this article - learning how to set up a local server environment and being able to run PHP.</p>\n<h2 id=\"part-2-setting-up-virtual-hosts\"><a href=\"#part-2-setting-up-virtual-hosts\" aria-label=\"part 2 setting up virtual hosts permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Part 2: Setting Up Virtual Hosts</h2>\n<p>In the next part, I'm going to show you how to have a multi-environment setup.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.taniarascia.com/setting-up-virtual-hosts\">Setting up virtual hosts</a></p>","timeToRead":5,"excerpt":"My early experiences with web design and development only involved the front end - HTML, CSS and some JavaScript. As long as I had a browser…","frontmatter":{"title":"Setting Up a Local Server Environment","thumbnail":{"childImageSharp":{"fixed":{"base64":"data:image/png;base64,","width":150,"height":150,"src":"/static/c24cec94464217841ac4ad8ad9b93339/4148e/mamp.png","srcSet":"/static/c24cec94464217841ac4ad8ad9b93339/4148e/mamp.png 1x"}}},"slug":"local-environment","date":"2015-10-17T00:00:00.000Z","categories":["Tools"],"tags":["php","setup"],"template":"post"},"fields":{"slug":"/local-environment/","date":"2015-10-17T00:00:00.000Z"}}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"slug":"/local-environment/"}}}